1
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:30,100
ETHAN: <i>It's been the same dream
every night for months now.</i>

2
00:00:30,100 --> 00:00:31,800
(THUNDER CRASHES)

3
00:00:32,900 --> 00:00:35,900
<i>I can't ever see her face, but I know her.</i>

4
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,100
<i>Like I've known her all my life.</i>

5
00:00:38,700 --> 00:00:42,500
<i>And it feels like something terrible
is gonna happen when I reach her.</i>

6
00:00:42,600 --> 00:00:45,600
<i>But at the same time, I'm not scared at all.</i>

7
00:00:46,200 --> 00:00:47,700
<i>I want her...</i>

8
00:00:47,900 --> 00:00:49,800
<i>...no matter what happens.</i>

9
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:51,400
<i>But I never get to her.</i>

10
00:00:51,900 --> 00:00:52,900
<i>And then I die.</i>

11
00:00:53,100 --> 00:00:54,100
(GUNSHOT)

12
00:00:54,300 --> 00:00:55,600
(GASPS)

13
00:00:57,100 --> 00:01:00,100
<i>At first I was scared I was losing my mind.</i>

14
00:01:00,200 --> 00:01:02,300
<i>Until I realized that would be no great toss.</i>

15
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:06,700
<i>I start junior year tomorrow,
so insanity's inevitable.</i>

16
00:01:07,700 --> 00:01:10,200
<i>What's worse is waking up every night...</i>

17
00:01:10,400 --> 00:01:13,200
<i>...wanting someone I've never met...</i>

18
00:01:13,300 --> 00:01:16,500
<i>...loving a girl who doesn't exist.</i>

19
00:01:31,300 --> 00:01:33,800
<i>I've been stuck my whole life in Gatlin...</i>

20
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:36,300
<i>...South Carolina's least-famous
middle-of-nowhere.</i>

21
00:01:36,500 --> 00:01:39,200
<i>By the time we get a movie,
it's already on DVD.</i>

22
00:01:39,400 --> 00:01:41,500
<i>And our theater always gets the titles wrong.</i>

23
00:01:43,300 --> 00:01:46,900
<i>We're too far away from Charleston
to have a Starbucks. How sick is that?</i>

24
00:01:56,400 --> 00:01:58,800
<i>We have 12 churches and one library...</i>

25
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:01,800
<i>...with more banned books
than books to read.</i>

26
00:02:01,900 --> 00:02:05,200
<i>Same damn families
have lived here for generations.</i>

27
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:08,900
<i>They keep reenacting the Civil War
like it's gonna turn out different.</i>

28
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:12,400
<i>Mama used to say there's only two kinds
of people in Gatlin:</i>

29
00:02:12,600 --> 00:02:16,900
<i>The ones too stupid to leave
and the ones too stuck to move.</i>

30
00:02:19,400 --> 00:02:21,900
<i>Dad can't leave his room since she died.</i>

31
00:02:22,700 --> 00:02:24,900
<i>People said it was God's will.</i>

32
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:28,200
<i>I think it's the only way people
ever get out of here.</i>

33
00:02:29,800 --> 00:02:33,600
<i>I can understand why young men
signed up for the Civil War.</i>

34
00:02:33,700 --> 00:02:36,200
<i>Anything is better than a life standing still.</i>

35
00:02:44,500 --> 00:02:47,900
<i>But I think even the dead stay in Gatlin.</i>

36
00:02:48,100 --> 00:02:52,500
<i>Sometimes, it sounds crazy,
but sometimes I imagine I'm one of them...</i>

37
00:02:52,700 --> 00:02:55,200
<i>...fighting for the cause
on Honey Hill near Greenbrier.</i>

38
00:02:55,300 --> 00:02:56,700
(VOICES SHOUTING)
(GUNSHOT)

39
00:02:56,800 --> 00:02:58,500
GENEVIEVE: <i>Ethan!</i>

40
00:03:22,400 --> 00:03:25,300
ETHAN: <i>
I imagine all kinds of things lately.</i>

41
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:27,900
<i>Sometimes...</i>

42
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:29,500
<i>...I'm Billy Pilgrim...</i>

43
00:03:29,700 --> 00:03:32,700
<i>...from Vonnegut's banned book
Slaughterhouse-Five.</i>

44
00:03:32,900 --> 00:03:37,100
<i>"To be unstuck in time,
in a constant state of stage fright...</i>

45
00:03:37,300 --> 00:03:41,500
<i>...never knowing what part of my fife
I'd have to act in next."</i>

46
00:03:41,700 --> 00:03:43,700
<i>I just love the sound of that.</i>

47
00:03:46,300 --> 00:03:47,800
Dad?

48
00:03:49,100 --> 00:03:50,900
Dad?

49
00:03:51,700 --> 00:03:53,900
I got breakfast.

50
00:03:58,900 --> 00:04:03,600
Ugh. Is this what we're wearing
our first day of school?

51
00:04:04,100 --> 00:04:08,400
I'm a junior now, Amma.
If I dress like I care, I lose credibility.

52
00:04:09,100 --> 00:04:10,800
I thought you were getting a haircut.

53
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:12,600
- Who said that?
- I did.

54
00:04:13,300 --> 00:04:15,800
Pay attention to the days
marked on these containers.

55
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,800
- Thanks, Amma.
- You decide what colleges you applying to?

56
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:22,000
All of them, as long as they're
a thousand miles away from here.

57
00:04:22,100 --> 00:04:23,500
Amen to that.

58
00:04:23,700 --> 00:04:26,100
- You go running last night?
- Yeah.

59
00:04:26,300 --> 00:04:30,100
- Help you sleep any?
- I envy people in comas.

60
00:04:30,700 --> 00:04:32,400
Your father come out at all?

61
00:04:33,300 --> 00:04:34,800
No.

62
00:04:37,700 --> 00:04:40,500
MRS. LINCOLN:
Lying lips are abomination to the Lord.

63
00:04:40,700 --> 00:04:44,900
Now, when a wicked man dies,
his expectation shall perish.

64
00:04:45,100 --> 00:04:48,900
And the hope of unjust men perisheth.

65
00:04:49,100 --> 00:04:50,100
Ow.

66
00:04:50,300 --> 00:04:52,900
- You get away now! Go on!
- Come on, I gotta take him to school!

67
00:04:53,100 --> 00:04:56,500
- We have to finish these. Do them tonight.
- Mom, you know what happens...

68
00:04:56,600 --> 00:04:59,700
Wesley, where are you going
without kissing your mother?

69
00:04:59,900 --> 00:05:02,200
What is wrong with you, boy, eh?

70
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:04,500
Now, you be good.

71
00:05:04,700 --> 00:05:07,600
- So is she a good kisser or what?
- Shut up!

72
00:05:07,800 --> 00:05:11,300
My mother has officially flown
that extra bat-shit mile since Dad died.

73
00:05:11,400 --> 00:05:15,300
She thinks the end of the world's coming
because all these earthquakes in the news.

74
00:05:15,500 --> 00:05:18,300
It's like, how does loving Jesus
make that woman so crazy?

75
00:05:18,500 --> 00:05:19,500
(ETHAN CHUCKLES)

76
00:05:19,700 --> 00:05:23,300
She damned Daddy to hell so many times,
I bet he drank just so he'd get there quicker.

77
00:05:23,400 --> 00:05:27,200
ETHAN: My dad is acting like old man
Ravenwood. They're all bat-shit.

78
00:05:27,400 --> 00:05:30,800
Hey, did you hear that new girl
in our class is a Ravenwood?

79
00:05:30,900 --> 00:05:33,600
I thought old man Ravenwood
lived in that house all alone.

80
00:05:33,800 --> 00:05:36,000
It's his niece from out of town.
She moved here.

81
00:05:36,100 --> 00:05:38,200
- Why would anyone move here?
- I don't know.

82
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:42,300
It'll be the first Ravenwood anybody
in Gatling's seen in almost 20 years.

83
00:05:45,100 --> 00:05:46,800
How was your summer, sugar?

84
00:05:47,600 --> 00:05:50,600
- Fine, Emily. And yours?
- Wonderful.

85
00:05:50,800 --> 00:05:54,200
Why didn't you go to the Labor Day Carnival?
It was such a good time.

86
00:05:54,700 --> 00:05:56,200
I wasn't up for it, heh.

87
00:05:56,900 --> 00:05:59,600
I don't understand what's happened.

88
00:05:59,700 --> 00:06:02,200
I know you don't. I'm sorry.

89
00:06:02,400 --> 00:06:05,100
You said to give you the summer, and I did.

90
00:06:05,300 --> 00:06:09,000
I didn't hear from you once,
but I was a good girl.

91
00:06:09,100 --> 00:06:10,700
I didn't call.

92
00:06:10,900 --> 00:06:12,600
But I missed you.

93
00:06:13,700 --> 00:06:17,000
Hey, no big deal, right?

94
00:06:17,100 --> 00:06:19,400
How's about you and I go see a movie
or something?

95
00:06:19,600 --> 00:06:21,800
Just us. Oh, that would be just heaven. Heh.

96
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:23,200
Sure.

97
00:06:23,300 --> 00:06:24,500
(BELL RINGING)

98
00:06:24,700 --> 00:06:26,700
MR. LEE: Everyone, take your seats.

99
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:29,500
Ethan, baby, I wish you'd quit reading
those kind of books.

100
00:06:29,600 --> 00:06:31,800
They're bad for your mind.

101
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:41,100
As a requirement of this course...

102
00:06:41,200 --> 00:06:44,500
...you will need to select a topic
for a term paper...

103
00:06:44,700 --> 00:06:48,100
...based on materials
covered in chapters 12 through 24.

104
00:06:48,300 --> 00:06:51,100
SAVANNAH: - Is that her?
EMILY: - Must be. What is she wearing?

105
00:06:51,300 --> 00:06:54,700
She looks like death eating a cracker.

106
00:06:54,900 --> 00:06:58,900
Now, just take any seat, miss, uh, uh...?

107
00:06:59,100 --> 00:07:02,100
Ravenwood. Isn't it?

108
00:07:02,200 --> 00:07:06,700
Mama says nobody's seen old man Ravenwood
leave that creepy house in years.

109
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:10,400
- Mama says he's a devil worshiper.
LENA: - Actually, it's Duchannes.

110
00:07:11,700 --> 00:07:14,700
Well, uh, now, that's an out-and-out lie.

111
00:07:14,800 --> 00:07:18,500
I happen to know for a fact
that you're Macon Ravenwood's niece.

112
00:07:20,100 --> 00:07:24,600
Well, bless your heart, sugar.
You must have been first in your litter.

113
00:07:24,800 --> 00:07:26,600
STUDENTS: Ooh.

114
00:07:27,800 --> 00:07:31,600
Mama says devil worshipers
hate fresh air. Makes them choke.

115
00:07:31,700 --> 00:07:33,300
Well, we all know what makes you choke.

116
00:07:33,400 --> 00:07:34,500
(STUDENTS CHATTERING)

117
00:07:34,600 --> 00:07:36,000
MR. LEE:
That's enough, Mr. Lincoln.

118
00:07:36,100 --> 00:07:39,100
- And that hat's gonna look nice on my cat.
- He's such a fool!

119
00:07:39,200 --> 00:07:43,700
MR. LEE: This year, you will participate
in the annual reenactment...

120
00:07:44,600 --> 00:07:46,900
...of our glorious victory:

121
00:07:47,100 --> 00:07:49,100
The Battle of Honey Hill.

122
00:07:49,200 --> 00:07:50,600
(STUDENTS GROANING AND MURMURING)

123
00:07:50,700 --> 00:07:51,700
Ethan?

124
00:07:51,900 --> 00:07:55,600
MR. LEE: The reenactment will be held
on the day of the battle, December the 21st.

125
00:07:55,700 --> 00:07:58,200
Even though that is the middle
of Christmas Break...

126
00:07:58,300 --> 00:08:02,500
...you will be expected
to participate wholeheartedly.

127
00:08:02,700 --> 00:08:05,400
(BOB DYLAN'S "SUBTERRANEAN HOME-SICK
BLUES" PLAYING ON CAR RADIO)

128
00:08:05,600 --> 00:08:07,700
(SINGING)
<i>Gel' sick, get well, hang around an ink well</i>

129
00:08:07,800 --> 00:08:10,300
<i>Ring bell, hard to tell
If anything is going to sell</i>

130
00:08:10,400 --> 00:08:11,500
<i>Try hard</i>

131
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:13,800
(MUMBLING LYRICS)

132
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:19,900
(GASPS)

133
00:08:20,100 --> 00:08:21,300
(TIRES SCREECH)

134
00:08:21,900 --> 00:08:23,800
Are you nuts? You almost killed me!

135
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:26,000
What are you doing
standing in the damn road?

136
00:08:26,200 --> 00:08:28,600
I need help, genius!

137
00:08:28,800 --> 00:08:31,500
- Forget it!
- Wait, wait, wait!

138
00:08:31,600 --> 00:08:34,000
I'm sorry! Look, get in!

139
00:08:34,100 --> 00:08:37,300
This is a shortcut, nobody
comes down this road. You'll drown...

140
00:08:37,500 --> 00:08:41,100
- Is this old man Ravenwood's car?
- You're one of them, aren't you?

141
00:08:41,200 --> 00:08:45,800
What are you?
The All-American jock star, prom king...

142
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:49,100
- ...jock?
- Look, can you insult me in the car?

143
00:08:49,300 --> 00:08:52,000
It's getting a little <i>Titanic</i> out here.

144
00:08:55,600 --> 00:08:58,500
You know, I never understood
why Leo had to die in the end.

145
00:08:58,600 --> 00:09:00,000
Why couldn't they take turns?

146
00:09:00,100 --> 00:09:03,900
"You float on the wooden thing 10 minutes,
I'll float on the thing 10 minutes."

147
00:09:04,100 --> 00:09:07,700
She kept saying, "I'll never let you go, never,"
and then she lets him go!

148
00:09:07,800 --> 00:09:11,300
If I get in the car, will there be more
of this fascinating conversation?

149
00:09:11,500 --> 00:09:13,500
Because I'd rather drown.

150
00:09:19,800 --> 00:09:21,500
No, I got groceries back there.

151
00:09:21,600 --> 00:09:24,300
I can't believe you told me
the ending to Titanic.

152
00:09:24,500 --> 00:09:27,100
- You've never seen it?
- No.

153
00:09:29,600 --> 00:09:31,600
You really are from out of town.

154
00:09:37,800 --> 00:09:39,100
Hey.

155
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:41,200
Thanks.

156
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:45,400
You know where you're going?

157
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:48,400
Rarely.

158
00:09:50,400 --> 00:09:53,600
Hey, I'm sorry about those clichés in class,
but I'm not one of them.

159
00:09:53,800 --> 00:09:54,800
"Clichés"?

160
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:59,400
Girls who once were human, but for whom
absolute popularity has corrupted absolutely.

161
00:09:59,600 --> 00:10:04,200
Hmm, bet you're real proud of yourself thinking
that one up. You probably dated one of them.

162
00:10:06,400 --> 00:10:09,900
- You out Emily like a surgeon.
- Years working with the bitch virus.

163
00:10:10,100 --> 00:10:12,900
- No cure yet, huh?
- We continue to research and hope.

164
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:15,700
- You been to a lot of schools?
- Yeah.

165
00:10:15,900 --> 00:10:18,800
- That must be nice. I've only ever lived here.
- Must be nice.

166
00:10:21,600 --> 00:10:23,000
So where y'all lived?

167
00:10:23,100 --> 00:10:26,100
Pretty much every state
that seceded from the Union.

168
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:29,100
Moved around since I was 4,
after my parents died.

169
00:10:29,300 --> 00:10:32,200
I only have my dad, my mom died
last spring. How did it happen?

170
00:10:33,500 --> 00:10:36,800
- Fire.
- Car accident.

171
00:10:38,800 --> 00:10:39,800
(STAMMERS)

172
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:44,400
Ha, ha, that was a dead-end conversation
on a road going nowhere.

173
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:47,000
I must have missed the exit to "fascinating,"
heh.

174
00:10:49,700 --> 00:10:51,400
You, uh...

175
00:10:51,900 --> 00:10:54,100
Bukowski? He...? He any good?

176
00:10:56,100 --> 00:10:57,600
Define "good."

177
00:10:59,400 --> 00:11:01,000
(CHUCKLES)

178
00:11:04,800 --> 00:11:06,900
ETHAN: - I can drive you to the house.
LENA: - This is fine.

179
00:11:07,100 --> 00:11:10,000
ETHAN: - No, I don't mind.
- Look, I appreciate the ride...

180
00:11:10,100 --> 00:11:13,200
...but I don't feel like being a haunted house
attraction today.

181
00:11:13,300 --> 00:11:16,700
No, I... Now, that's fairly rude
and not true at all.

182
00:11:16,900 --> 00:11:19,800
Perhaps it's because
we haven't been properly introduced.

183
00:11:19,900 --> 00:11:21,500
I'm Ethan Wate, by the way.

184
00:11:21,700 --> 00:11:24,500
- You're Ethan Wate?
- Yeah.

185
00:11:24,700 --> 00:11:27,400
Oh, my God, you mean
Ethan Wate drove me home?

186
00:11:27,500 --> 00:11:29,900
- You've heard of me?
- No.

187
00:11:30,300 --> 00:11:31,300
(ETHAN CHUCKLES)

188
00:11:31,500 --> 00:11:33,300
I like your charm necklace.

189
00:11:33,400 --> 00:11:37,400
And... And your tat, too. I mean, uh, also.

190
00:11:38,300 --> 00:11:39,300
Thanks.

191
00:11:39,500 --> 00:11:41,000
(ETHAN CHUCKLES)

192
00:11:42,800 --> 00:11:45,200
ETHAN: <i>"Some people never go crazy.</i>

193
00:11:45,400 --> 00:11:48,400
<i>What truly horrible lives they must live.</i>

194
00:11:48,500 --> 00:11:51,700
<i>Boring damned people. All over the Earth.</i>

195
00:11:51,900 --> 00:11:56,200
<i>Propagating more boring damned people.
What a horror show.</i>

196
00:11:56,400 --> 00:11:59,200
<i>The Earth swarmed with them."</i>

197
00:12:00,600 --> 00:12:03,200
This man is a god.

198
00:12:24,100 --> 00:12:27,900
MRS. LINCOLN: It is the name of our Lord
that brings salvation.

199
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:32,500
It is the name of Jesus
that gives us authority over evil spirits.

200
00:12:32,700 --> 00:12:34,000
(CHATTERING)

201
00:12:34,100 --> 00:12:35,800
- What's going on?
- Here, just wait for it.

202
00:12:35,900 --> 00:12:38,600
MRS. LINCOLN: Protect us from the devil,
as we feel him approaching.

203
00:12:38,800 --> 00:12:40,200
As we feel him coming towards us...

204
00:12:40,400 --> 00:12:41,400
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

205
00:12:41,600 --> 00:12:43,700
- Been hitting the same spot every night.
- Since when?

206
00:12:43,800 --> 00:12:47,300
EMILY: Since Lena Duchannes came to town.
My mama heard she's from a mental institution.

207
00:12:47,500 --> 00:12:49,600
She killed a boy
on the train tracks in Atlanta.

208
00:12:49,700 --> 00:12:51,100
ETHAN: - Oh, bullshit.
LINK: - Bullshit.

209
00:12:51,300 --> 00:12:52,300
Watch your tongue.

210
00:12:52,500 --> 00:12:56,300
My mama said that her mother
killed her father and just left town like that.

211
00:12:56,400 --> 00:12:58,800
Shut your mouth, Emily.

212
00:12:59,700 --> 00:13:02,800
Ethan Wate,
may I speak with you for a moment?

213
00:13:02,900 --> 00:13:04,600
Right now?

214
00:13:06,400 --> 00:13:07,800
What is wrong with you?

215
00:13:07,900 --> 00:13:11,600
I'm just sick of people in this town putting
down someone they just don't know.

216
00:13:11,800 --> 00:13:12,900
(EMILY CHUCKLES)

217
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:16,100
And you know Lena Duchannes?

218
00:13:16,800 --> 00:13:19,000
Is that what you're saying, Ethan?

219
00:13:19,400 --> 00:13:23,400
Sorry, but I don't think I'm gonna be able
to go to the movies with you this weekend.

220
00:13:23,600 --> 00:13:25,800
I think we need time apart.

221
00:13:25,900 --> 00:13:28,100
And I'm sorry to hurt you.

222
00:13:29,400 --> 00:13:30,900
Let's go.

223
00:13:31,900 --> 00:13:35,200
Did I not say that to her
at the end of sophomore year?

224
00:13:35,400 --> 00:13:38,200
Hey, some girls are just mad dogs, son.

225
00:13:38,300 --> 00:13:41,500
You can either run or shoot.

226
00:13:41,600 --> 00:13:43,400
(CHATTERING)

227
00:13:49,300 --> 00:13:51,600
EMILY: Ethan? Ethan.

228
00:13:51,800 --> 00:13:54,000
Can I talk to you
about something real quick?

229
00:13:54,100 --> 00:13:55,800
I want you to know something.

230
00:13:56,000 --> 00:13:58,700
